    "You move out toward the tidal flats to oversee the fragile gear you can still salvage. The walk from the glasshouse to the shore is a corridor of weather: the wind has picked up, changing from"
    "brisk to insistently cold; the sky is a bruise. You can taste ozone; your clothes cling damply. Footsteps slap the mud, and every now and then a shout from the far-off evacuation channels — names, addresses,"
    "the sound of urgency like a chorus of broken bells."
    "At the flats, the test long-lines bob like ghost ropes in the swollen tide. Volunteers work with frantic, choreographed motions: tying, hauling, cutting, sometimes cursing. The sea is relentless, washing at the pilings in a rhythm that feels like counting down."

    "Mika (from the trailer)" "Sensors going dark in sector three. If the water reaches the low node, the anchor's torque will shear the ties."

    marina_reyes "We cut then. We pull the lines we can. Anything that will drag the buoys into the channel comes with us."

    "A man you recognize — a volunteer who had argued with Old Tom about net-mending last week — yells over, voice raw" "You're pulling them? What about the beds? What about the lease we have with the fishers?"

    marina_reyes "These are experiments. If they break they'll contaminate everything. We take what's salvageable now; we keep the templates. I promise we'll rebuild — we have to be able to rebuild."
    "Promises feel thin. You sense them fraying in your hands like old rope. Someone spits a bitter word you can't make out exactly, and it lodges in your throat."
    "Kaori 'Kai' Matsuda is at the lead line, hands moving with practiced speed. For one split second she looks up at you, face gray and lit from below by her headlamp, then goes right back to work."

    kaori_kai_matsuda "You're keeping the archive. You're trading the crowd's momentum for a slow seed."

    marina_reyes "If we keep nothing, there's no 'momentum' to spend. There's only loss."
    "The tide comes in faster than expected. A wave hits the planked walkway and throws a sheet of saltwater over everything. Your gloves are full of stinging salt. You can taste iron and fear."
    "Amalia appears at your elbow, crying now but trying to smile."
    show amalia_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    amalia_reyes "Some people already left their doors open. They thought you'd...they thought you'd organize a convoy—"

    marina_reyes "We called the routes. We staged the pickups. Some refused — said they'd rather sit on their porches than load a truck."

    amalia_reyes "They're saying you hid the cooperative's trucks. They're saying you were planning this for months."
    "her voice fractures"

    amalia_reyes "They think you chose the seeds over them."
    "The accusation is sharp enough to cut. You can feel the town's opinion like weather — it shifts and battering and unpredictable. Your buoy pendant presses cold."
    hide marina_reyes
    hide kaori_kai_matsuda
    hide amalia_reyes

    scene bg ch14_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The tide's roar; an alarm chirps from a remote sensor; someone sobs near a truck]
    "You are exhausted in a way that isn't physical yet. The decision has weight. You can hear it: the thump of the generator, the slap of the tide, the murmur of a crowd forming like distant thunder."
    show mika_tran at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mika_tran "Do we send the crates out with the evacuation? We have space for two, maybe three if we compress the manifests."
    show marina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_reyes "We send them with priority. We label chain-of-custody. Whoever takes them goes to the school gym's secure wing. No one touches them but people we log. Amalia, you'll take the manifest with you and read names aloud while we pack."
    show amalia_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    amalia_reyes "I'll read them. I'll read them like a prayer."
    "Your hands shake as you tape the last crate. A volunteer slams the van door shut; someone curses. On the other side of the flats, a small knot of people gather, faces bright with lantern-light, mouths"
    "moving in rapid, angry phrases. You can't hear the words exactly, but their tone is a blade."
    "You watch the crates as they are lifted. For a second you imagine the seedbank like a hearth: if the hearth lives, the house might be rebuilt. If the hearth dies, there's only cold."
    "Kaori 'Kai' Matsuda returns to the glasshouse to help secure the backups. She doesn't say you're right; she doesn't say you're wrong. She moves with a tightness that makes you think of snapping."
    hide mika_tran
    show kaori_kai_matsuda at left:
        zoom 0.7

    kaori_kai_matsuda "When this is over, people will need hands to hold them. They'll need someone who didn't hide in a greenhouse."

    marina_reyes "If the greenhouse fails, they'll need hands that can read an old protocol and start the lines again. If the greenhouse succeeds, they'll have those hands."
    "your voice cracks"

    marina_reyes "I am trying to make sure there are hands to give."
    "The argument isn't for now. It's already an ember that will flare later when the town decides who led and who abandoned."

    menu:
        "Tell Kaori 'I know this will hurt her'":
            "You say it quieter than you feel: the words diffuse the crack but don't close it. Kaori gives a single, tight exhale and turns to the racks."
        "Force the order and move on":
            "Your voice hardens. People obey. Kaori's jaw works; she loads the last crate with a hand that trembles."

